"categories":null,"content":"Primordial black holes\n","date":-62135596800,"expirydate":-62135596800,"kind":"page","lang":"en","lastmod":-62135596800,"objectID":"4364afc3f27b6239087b33bdf1f69d1d","permalink":"https://example.com/project/pbh/","publishdate":"0001-01-01T00:00:00Z","relpermalink":"/project/pbh/","section":"project","summary":"Searching for planetary-mass inspiraling primordial black hole binaries.","tags":["Primordial black holes"],"title":"Detecting gravitational waves from sub-solar mass primordial black holes","type":"project"},{"authors":null,"categories":null,"content":"Detector glitches\n","date":-62135596800,"expirydate":-62135596800,"kind":"page","lang":"en","lastmod":-62135596800,"objectID":"82f75aee85c6e5d03be4d41606e2c034","permalink":"https://example.com/project/ml-glitches/","publishdate":"0001-01-01T00:00:00Z","relpermalink":"/project/ml-glitches/","section":"project","summary":"Identifying different kinds of glitches in LIGO data using auxiliary channels","tags":["machine learning"],"title":"Detector glitch classification with machine learning","type":"project"},{"authors":null,"categories":null,"content":"Dark photon dark matter\n","date":-62135596800,"expirydate":-62135596800,"kind":"page","lang":"en","lastmod":-62135596800,"objectID":"2428ed3aff1c4b4edda49ea3449c88ec","permalink":"https://example.com/project/dpdm/","publishdate":"0001-01-01T00:00:00Z","relpermalink":"/project/dpdm/","section":"project","summary":"Searching for dark photon dark matter coupling to baryons in the LIGO mirrors","tags":["Dark matter"],"title":"Directly detecting particle dark matter with LIGO, Virgo and KAGRA","type":"project"},{"authors":null,"categories":null,"content":"Detector glitches\n","date":-62135596800,"expirydate":-62135596800,"kind":"page","lang":"en","lastmod":-62135596800,"objectID":"50aa08de3e40eaaeecb942203cb074d9","permalink":"https://example.com/project/ml-cw/","publishdate":"0001-01-01T00:00:00Z","relpermalink":"/project/ml-cw/","section":"project","summary":"Convolutional neural networks to search for continuous waves from isolated neutron stars in non-Gaussian noise","tags":["Machine learning"],"title":"Machine learning to detect continuous gravitational waves","type":"project"},{"authors":null,"categories":null,"content":"Multi-messenger astronomy\n","date":-62135596800,"expirydate":-62135596800,"kind":"page","lang":"en","lastmod":-62135596800,"objectID":"a3bb6873323fe1c6ad58a053a3f6f626","permalink":"https://example.com/project/mmcw/","publishdate":"0001-01-01T00:00:00Z","relpermalink":"/project/mmcw/","section":"project","summary":"Early warning and sky localization of binary neutron star inspirals in Einstein Telescope using continuous waves methods","tags":["Multi-messenger astronomy"],"title":"Multi-messenger astronomy with continuous gravitational waves","type":"project"},{"authors":["Andrew L. Miller"],"categories":null,"content":"Overview Deformed, isolated neutron stars could spin down due to the loss of energy via gravitational waves. The timescale of energy loss greatly exceeds that of the observation time of the LIGO-Virgo-KAGRA detectors, and the gravitational-wave frequency is almost constant; hence, these signals are called continuous gravitational waves. The gravitational-wave signal is also Doppler modulated, due to the relative motion of the earth with respect to the source. In this tutorial, we show how a simulated continuous gravitationanl-wave signal from a particular sky location is recovered with a pattern recognition technique called the Hough Transform. You can access the tutorial on google collab. ","date":-62135596800,"expirydate":-62135596800,"kind":"page","lang":"en","lastmod":-62135596800,"objectID":"d9205d677dd3273d0c28c9ffc0330708","permalink":"https://example.com/post/tutorial/","publishdate":"0001-01-01T00:00:00Z","relpermalink":"/post/tutorial/","section":"post","summary":"Learn about searching for quasi-monochromatic, persistent gravitational waves from isolated neutron stars in this tutorial.","tags":null,"title":"Tutorial on the frequency-Hough transform to search for continuous gravitational waves","type":"post"}]